Walter son os Ralph le Lord v. T Ιιι Prior (pp. 163-5). Writ of wardship. The demandant claims the wardship of a moiety of certain tenements in barton on the ground that the late tenant of the tenemento held of the demandant by military service. The Prior pleads that he is holding the moiety as the right of his church and therefore need not answer to a writ of wardship. The demandant replies and the Prior rejoins‚ and judgment is given for the Prior as upon a demurrer. The facts which occasioned this dispute are very curious; but they are clearly stated by the narrator and must not be suffered to delay us.

Ilu Prior v. Wan'rr de L’Isle (pp. 165-6). Writ of customs and services. No record is given. We are told however that by way of defence Warin produced a spurious charter. Thereupon the Prior was advised to claim the land in demesne‚ and the tenant hastened to make his peace.

Some further accounts of litigation—not records-bring us to the end of what happened in the Cambridge eyre of 1286 (pp. 166-71). The memoriallst is not a little triumphant over the Prioffs many successes, but is exceed- ingly frank in telling us how the favour of the justices and of their clerks was secured by generous hospitality.

We come next to a very interesting tale of prolonged litigation in the Courts Christian between the Prior and the Vicat of Guilden Morden (pp. 171-61 1t shows us a seamy side of ecclesiastica} affairs. However‚ the documents which were indited in the course of this obstinate struggle are not transcribed. Probably they would have filled a large book. .

There follows a suit in an ecclesiastical court, before the official of the Bishop of Norwich for a legacy bequeathed to the Priory by Eva Pecchd (p. 176).
